"""constants.py — leaf module: the daemon's load-bearing constants.

Extracted (DA-CONST-01, daemon-architecture-v2) so version/port config
lives in a dependency-free leaf that ANY module can import without a
cycle back to daemon.py — unblocking the selfupdate/bootstrap splits.
No sibling imports. bundle.py reads DAEMON_VERSION from HERE for the
early 8 KB version marker; MODULES inlines constants.py FIRST.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import os
from pathlib import Path


PORT_RANGE = (5570, 5589)

# Release-signing PUBLIC key (Ed25519, hex). py-1.27.5. The daemon verifies
# every self-update bundle's detached signature (`<url>.sig`) against this
# pinned key before swapping + re-exec'ing — so a CDN compromise / MITM
# can't push code that runs as the operator. The matching PRIVATE seed
# lives ONLY at daemon/.release-signing-key (gitignored, off-CDN) and is
# used by bundle.py at release time. Rotating the key = regenerate the
# seed, re-pin this hex, redeploy (old daemons that already trust the old
# key will reject the new build until they update through a key-overlap
# release — see workflows/W2). Empty string = signature checks disabled.
RELEASE_PUBKEY_HEX = "9699b5c93066195d85e974a1bca9ace6931ea31a21e347414d6f0a34d55b13cb"
# py-1.15.0 — machine-global sticky port registry (cluster_id → port).
# Lives outside any repo so every daemon on this box shares one source of
# truth and a cluster ALWAYS comes back up on the same port (no drift).
# py-1.16.0 (D-TEST-ISO-01) — MESHKORE_PORTS_FILE overrides the registry
# path so the test suite (which spawns real daemon subprocesses) points it
# at a tmp file instead of polluting the operator's real ~/.meshkore.
_PORT_REGISTRY_FILE = Path(
    os.environ.get("MESHKORE_PORTS_FILE") or (Path.home() / ".meshkore" / "ports.json")
)
_PORT_REGISTRY_DIR = _PORT_REGISTRY_FILE.parent
FS_POLL_SEC = 1.5
DAEMON_VERSION = "py-1.28.1"  # 1.28.1 — TASK FAILURE RESOLUTION. `_persist_task_resolution` (anchorprogress.py) now records a `## Resolution` for FAILED turns too, not just `done`: a non-zero exit (after the TR1 transient-retry shield) marks the anchored task `blocked` + `failed_at` and writes the failure reason (+ files touched) into the body. Before, failed/blocked tasks carried NO resolution → the cockpit's RES line was empty. Now every terminal task turn has content: SUCCESS → blue RES (completed_at/resolved_by + summary), FAILURE → red RES (blocked + reason). Lets the operator see WHY a queue item stopped + intervene. Already-`done` tasks aren't reopened on a late non-zero. 1.28.0 — CONTEXT-WINDOW AWARENESS (CTX1, initiative `active-context-management`). New `contextpolicy.py`: a per-PLATFORM context policy. claude-code knows its model→window map (200k default; 1M for the `[1m]` variants) + self-compacts WITHIN a turn; an UNMODELLED runtime (DeepSeek/Codex/raw API) gets a null policy — no gauge, no compaction claim — so the daemon never assumes claude-code behaviour for a client it doesn't model. `chat.usage` WS events now carry a `context` block {platform, window, prompt_tokens, fill_ratio, supports_compaction, threshold(0.5), should_compact} so the cockpit paints a context-fill gauge (the "little circle" the operator watches) + a will-compact hint. KEY ARCHITECTURE NOTE: MeshKore runs each turn as a FRESH `claude -p` fed a daemon-built briefing over stdin (no persistent session since the py-1.6.1 hotfix disabled --session-id) — so WITHIN a turn Claude owns the window (we only READ usage, never fight it); ACROSS turns the daemon owns context (the briefing's rolling history). fill_ratio measures what the model READ this turn (input_tokens + both cache buckets) / window, bound to the agent type's `platform` via agent_types._agent_manifest. This is the MEASUREMENT+SIGNAL layer; CTX2 (at threshold, delegate a real summarisation to the model + emit context.compressing, rebuild the briefing from a frozen summary) is the planned follow-up. New module wired into bundle.py MODULES (after constants.py — pure, no sibling deps) + runnerloop usage broadcast. tests/test_contextpolicy.py (6 pure unit tests). 1.27.6 — LOCAL auto-unlock (operator: a token for your OWN local daemon is pointless friction; the unlock prompt is only for the future CLOUD daemon). NEW `GET /auth/local-token` (routes_get.py) hands the bearer token to the SAME-ORIGIN cockpit page over loopback so a local project never prompts. Tightly gated: EXACT cockpit/loopback origins only (architect.meshkore.com / localhost / 127.0.0.1 — NOT the broad CORS *.pages.dev allowlist); a malicious website gets a different Origin (refused + CORS-unreadable). Residual multi-user-host caveat documented; opt out via cluster.yaml `daemon.local_token_auto: false`. The cockpit auto-fetches this for loopback clusters before ever showing the unlock UI. Pairs with cockpit self-healing reconnection (connection loss → center-zone OfflinePanel auto-retry + manual-restart guidance; the left projects rail is NEVER hidden by a project-scoped dialog). 1.27.5 — SIGNED SELF-UPDATE (operator-approved 2026-06-24). Closes the last real finding: auto-update was unsigned (only ast.parse + a DAEMON_VERSION marker), so a CDN compromise/MITM could swap in code that runs as the operator. Now every release is Ed25519-signed; the daemon pins the PUBLIC key (RELEASE_PUBKEY_HEX) and BOTH update paths (boot `_boot_self_update_if_needed` + HTTP `/self-update`) call `verify_release_bundle()` — fetch `<url>.sig`, verify the detached sig over the downloaded bytes against the pinned key — and REFUSE the swap on missing/invalid sig (keeps the running, trusted daemon). Stdlib-only: vendored pure-Python Ed25519 (crypto_ed25519.py, RFC-8032 reference, cross-checked byte-identical vs `cryptography`). Signing is automatic in bundle.py (reads the off-CDN private seed daemon/.release-signing-key → writes dist/daemon.py.sig); release = publish daemon.py + daemon.py.sig (workflow W2). Empty RELEASE_PUBKEY_HEX disables enforcement. 1.27.4 — TRUST/HARDENING pass (field report 2026-06-24: a security-conscious onboarding agent reviewing the bundle flagged the changelog's own wording as adversarial-to-AI-safety + found a real CORS gap). TWO fixes. (a) CORS: `_cors` (routes.py) no longer sends `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`. The bearer token gates writes, but the OPEN read routes (/state //agents //info //storage/usage) were cross-origin-readable by ANY site the operator visited while the daemon ran (project-state/agent-roster leak). Now reflects an ALLOWLISTED origin only (*.meshkore.com + *.pages.dev previews + loopback) via `_allowed_origin`, with `Vary: Origin`; any other origin gets NO Allow-Origin so the browser blocks the read. Same-origin / non-browser callers (no Origin header) unaffected. New test_cors.py. (b) HONEST FRAMING: the onboarding split is a SAFETY property, not a trick. The coding agent only does reversible/inspectable work (mkdir, git, curl, and the short-lived `init` scaffolder that writes text files and exits without opening a port); the HUMAN starts the long-lived daemon — which exposes a bearer-gated localhost shell-job endpoint the architect web app drives, so leaving that launch to the operator is correct hygiene. The design does NOT try to get an agent to start it unprompted; earlier 1.27.2 phrasing ("so the coding agent NEVER ... is NEVER prompted") described this same human/agent split badly and is corrected here. 1.27.3 — scaffold offline gate + test_scaffold.py. scaffold._fetch short-circuits to the offline fallback when MESHKORE_OFFLINE (air-gapped first boot no longer hangs ~16s on two failing api.meshkore.com fetches) or MESHKORE_DAEMON_NO_BOOT_UPDATE (the test suite's hermetic flag → init/auto-scaffold are deterministic + network-free under pytest, STANDARD_VERSION = DEFAULT_STANDARD_VERSION). NEW tests/test_scaffold.py: in-process unit tests (slugify_id pattern, full-tree write, schema-valid cluster.yaml via Cluster, gitignore deny-list, task_frontmatter, preamble markers + per-CLI render, refuse-clobber/--force, offline STANDARD_VERSION) + subprocess tests (init CLI scaffold + idempotent no-op exit-0, auto-scaffold-on-boot serves /health). 1.27.2 — AUTONOMY FIX (operator field report 2026-06-24: even with init, the onboarding agent STILL asked questions — running `daemon.py init` is "executing downloaded code" which coding agents pause on, and init refusing to clobber forced a --force question). TWO changes so the coding agent isn't ASKED to run untrusted long-lived code (the human starts the daemon; see 1.27.4 for the honest framing): (a) AUTO-SCAFFOLD ON FIRST BOOT — main() no longer SystemExits when cluster.yaml is missing but `.meshkore/` exists (agent downloaded the daemon to .meshkore/scripts/ but never ran init); it scaffolds (display name = folder name) then serves, so the operator's SINGLE launch command bootstraps everything. Still refuses if `.meshkore/` is wholly absent (wrong-dir guard). (b) `daemon.py init` on an already-scaffolded cluster is now a GRACEFUL no-op (exit 0 + "skipping" message) instead of a ScaffoldError — so an "init ; launch" one-liner is safe to re-paste and never triggers the --force question. genPrompt.ts rewritten so the agent ONLY creates the folder + curls daemon+TLS (no hand-written .meshkore files, no executing init/daemon) and prints the launch command for the operator. 1.27.1 — init .gitignore: ignore `.meshkore/scripts/` wholesale (was scripts/__pycache__ + scripts/tls/privkey.pem only). The downloaded daemon.py auto-updates → committing it churns diffs; the TLS bundle is re-fetchable + privkey is secret. So scripts/ is never committed, matching Standard v27 folder_layout (scripts committed:false) + §2.2 deny-list. Pairs with the Standard v27 git-contract bump (commit public/docs/modules/roadmap/initiatives; gitignore runtime/credentials/agents/timeline/log/queues/uploads/snapshots/state/roadmap-state/scripts). 1.27.0 — `daemon.py init` SELF-BOOTSTRAP (operator-directed 2026-06-23). The Architect "Add a project" prompt (genPrompt.ts) used to hand-write the entire .meshkore tree against the standard SCHEMA and DRIFTED hard: pinned to STANDARD_VERSION=7 while live was v26, `mkdir -p ${name}` broke on names with spaces ("Reddit intel" → TWO folders), wrote `id: <display name>` violating the `^[a-z0-9-]{2,40}$` pattern, and STOPPED to ask the operator for a description — so a bypass-mode run produced alerts + questions, not a clean cluster. FIX moves scaffolding INTO the daemon: NEW scaffold.py + `daemon.py init --name "<name>" [--id slug] [--desc …] [--force]` writes the full v26 layout (folder_layout dirs, public/cluster.yaml schema-correct, AGENT_INSTRUCTIONS.md + rendered CLAUDE/AGENTS/GEMINI/.cursor/.clinerules, docs/governance+INDEX, modules general+project READMEs, starter task with valid task_frontmatter, repo-root .gitignore deny-list committing public/docs/modules/roadmap) and pins STANDARD_VERSION to the LIVE published version (fetched, offline-fallback DEFAULT_STANDARD_VERSION=26) — so a fresh cluster is born at the CURRENT standard, never frozen behind, and the drift class is structurally impossible (the daemon writes what its own version mandates). slugify_id() mirrors genPrompt.ts. init runs BEFORE the `.meshkore` existence guard, refuses to clobber an existing cluster.yaml (--force overrides), exits without serving. Bundle: scaffold.py added to MODULES (after cluster.py); `import datetime as _dtmod` (the flat bundle namespace rebinds bare `datetime` to the CLASS). genPrompt.ts rewritten to download→init→run (~no schema decisions). DEFERRED: standard folder_layout committed-flags bump (blocked on pre-existing v25↔v26 surface drift — webapp/api-web at 25, api-edge/.meshkore at 26 — untangle that FIRST per §11). 1.26.1 — cockpit→"Architect IDE" in the agent briefing (prompts.py + _roadmap_architect); golden SHAs regenerated. Internal identifiers/CSS/historical changelogs keep the codename. 1.26.0 — RENAME "protocols" → "workflows" (operator-directed 2026-06-21). "protocol" is reserved in MeshKore for agent-COMMUNICATION standards (A2A/MCP/HTTP); an ordered operational runbook (deploy, audit, upgrade, PR-review) is a WORKFLOW (the term the AI/dev community uses — CI / agentic workflows). protocols.py → workflows.py (WorkflowsRegistry; ProtocolsRegistry kept as alias); paths gains workflows_dir/workflows_log (reads `.meshkore/workflows/`, falls back to legacy `.meshkore/protocols/`); registry globs BOTH `W<N>-` and legacy `P<N>-` files/logs; canonical endpoints `GET /workflows`, `/workflows/<id>`, `/workflows/<id>/runs`, with `/protocols*` kept as DEPRECATED ALIASES; broadcasts `workflows.updated` AND (deprecated) `protocols.updated` so an un-updated cockpit keeps working. Cluster folder `.meshkore/protocols/` → `.meshkore/workflows/` (P1–P7 → W1–W7 + run logs); convention doc protocols.md → workflows.md; INDEX + cross-refs updated. Standard §14 + cockpit panel are the follow-ups. Route-coverage warranty extended (/workflows + /protocols both exercised). 1.25.3 — AOF1 autonomous-output-feed (operator-directed 2026-06-20): the roadmap-architect chat should read as ONE continuous event feed, not fragmented per-turn blocks with repeated headers, and the content should be terse+useful (launched / finished + a 2-3 line human summary), not the internal VERDICT/MATRIX/preview plumbing. PROMPT half (here): `agent_prompts/_roadmap_architect.py` CHAT FORMAT rewritten — visible output is a stream of EVENT LINES (🚀 launched · ✓ finished + ≤3-line summary of WHAT CHANGED · ✗ blocked + reason); explicit rule to NEVER paste the `[architect-wake]`/`VERDICT:`/`MATRIX RULE`/sub-agent-preview text into chat (it's daemon→agent plumbing the operator can't see); long-form rationed to ONE pre-flight + ONE end-of-pass + ≤3-line per-initiative plan. Only the roadmap-architect briefing shifts (golden SHA regenerated for that one type). Pairs with cockpit AUTONOMOUS-RENDER: convs of an autonomous agent type render as a continuous timeline — consecutive agent finals grouped under a SINGLE header (chat-stream.groupAutonomous + ChatBubbles.AutonomousRun), the `architect-wake` plumbing messages HIDDEN, and an operator co-direction message rendered INLINE (chronological, NOT hoisted as "queued above") so it cleanly breaks the run and starts a fresh header. NO Standard/schema/wire change — the daemon still emits one chat.assistant.final per wave; grouping + hiding is cockpit-side, content is prompt-side. 1.25.2 — VRF8: drive the auto-DOWNLOADED Chrome-for-Testing reliably. Root cause was NOT the CDP transport — Python's zipfile.extractall DROPS unix exec bits, so CfT's helper binaries (chrome_crashpad_handler, Framework Helpers) unpacked non-executable → `FATAL chrome_crashpad_handler: Permission denied` → unstable browser whose DevTools ws reset on Target.attachToTarget (looked like a WS-transport bug across both py-1.25.0/.1 investigations). Fix: _download_chrome_for_testing now restores each zip entry's mode from external_attr on extract (POSIX). With perms intact the EXISTING stdlib WS transport drives CfT end-to-end (create→attach→navigate→screenshot, verified vs example.com) — no --remote-debugging-pipe rewrite needed. So the no-host-browser path is now fully working: download portable CfT into .meshkore/.runtime/browser/ and drive it headless. Removed the 1.25.1 "experimental, prefer host browser" download caveat (no longer true). No Standard bump. 1.25.1 — Verify hardening (operator review 2026-06-20). (a) The downloaded browser now lives INSIDE the cluster at `.meshkore/.runtime/browser/` (was the per-user OS cache) — `browser_dir` threads through ensure_browser/discover/download; `$MESHKORE_BROWSER_DIR` overrides; verifysvc passes `paths.runtime/browser`. (b) Credentialed pages: verify `state` now accepts `headers` / `basic_auth` / `cookies` (Network.setExtraHTTPHeaders + setCookies, applied BEFORE navigation) in addition to `localStorage` — a login-walled URL is reachable, or Verify honestly screenshots the login screen (never bypasses auth). (c) On-demand discovery: every agent's universal briefing now lists `POST /verify` as an ON-DEMAND capability (call it when asked to check the UI or when a render/flow looks broken — NOT per-edit; a copy change doesn't need it) with the credentialed-URL caveat — golden briefing SHAs regenerated. (d) CDP launch hardened: connect to the browser ws via the DevToolsActivePort port + its ws-path line directly (immediate poll-and-connect loop), skipping the racy `/json/version` HTTP round-trip — more reliable cold start. KNOWN GAP (VRF8): driving the auto-DOWNLOADED Chrome-for-Testing headless is still unreliable (CfT 150 resets the ws on Target.attachToTarget); the binary downloads fine but a host browser (Windows always has Edge; Chrome on mac/linux) is the supported path — ensure_browser logs this when it falls back to download. No Standard bump. 1.25.0 — MeshKore Verify VRF1+VRF2 (initiative `meshkore-verify`, local-first visual+functional verification; operator-directed 2026-06-20). NEW verify.py: a stdlib-only Chrome DevTools Protocol client (hand-rolled WebSocket over socket/struct/ssl — NO Playwright, NO pip dep, the single-`.py` zero-install distribution preserved) that DISCOVERS a host browser (Chrome/Brave/Edge on macOS; Edge ships with Windows → zero download) or downloads portable Chrome-for-Testing into the OS cache (a `.zip`, no installer, no admin, outside the project), and exposes `verify(spec)→evidence`: multi-viewport full-page screenshots (an agent reads the PNG with its own vision), console/network capture, layout heuristics (horizontal-overflow/longest-line), a step DSL (goto/click/fill/waitFor/assert), api checks, and a verdict — plus a standalone CLI. NEW verifysvc.py `VerifyMixin` on Daemon: POST /verify runs the embedded verifier (or proxies to a remote A2A verify agent when `cluster.yaml#verify.mode=agent`, VRF6), stores shots under `.meshkore/.runtime/verify/<conv>/`, serves them over loopback via GET /verify/shot?path=… (path-confined to the verify runtime dir, no traversal), and broadcasts a `verify.result` WS event for the cockpit Verify panel (VRF7). `cluster.yaml#verify` config (mode local|agent, agent_url, allow_download, default_viewports, inline_b64). bundle.py: verify.py+verifysvc.py added to MODULES + a new `_strip_main_block` that drops an inlined module's `if __name__=="__main__"` block (only daemon.py, inlined LAST, keeps its entrypoint) — without it verify.py's argparse CLI ran FIRST in the bundle and consumed the daemon's --port/--root argv → daemon exited early (caught by test_parity). Closes the blind-agent loop: agent edits UI → POST /verify renders it on the host → agent sees the PNGs → fix → re-verify until verdict:pass. Engine decision supersedes VRF1's original Playwright plan (incompatible with the stdlib single-file daemon). Post-task auto-hook deferred to VRF4's `verify:` frontmatter (`VerifyMixin.run_for_spec` core already in place). Route-coverage warranty + parity tests extended for /verify + /verify/shot; full daemon suite 223 passed. 1.24.2 — AS2 anchor reuse-archived-stories (operator-directed 2026-06-20): when an agent searches for the initiative to anchor to, the search must span ARCHIVED stories too, not only active ones — an old work-stream that's being resumed/widened (e.g. a finished `web-redesign` you're extending) should be REUSED rather than re-minted as a near-duplicate. TWO halves. (a) DAEMON (anchor.py): `_resolve_init_path(slug)` now resolves an initiative across BOTH `.meshkore/roadmap/initiatives/` AND `.meshkore/roadmap/initiatives/log/` (the archive — superseded/closed work-streams are MOVED there by the split/close protocol, so the old `.exists()` on the live folder alone could never match an archived slug → hard-rejected the anchor). `_handle_anchor` uses it for both the `i` and `new_t.initiative` branches. When the resolved initiative is archived (in `log/`) or closed (`status: done|superseded|archived`), `_reactivate_init` brings it back into the live roadmap: moves the file out of `log/`, flips status→active, bumps `updated:`, stamps `reactivated:`. The `conv.anchored` event gains a `reactivated` bool and triggers a state rebuild so the reopened story repaints. (b) PROMPT (prompts.py decision chain): the agent is now told to read `initiatives/log/` as well as the active folder, to PREFER reusing an existing story — even archived — over a near-duplicate, and that anchoring a `t`/`new_t` to an archived slug auto-reactivates it; mint a NEW initiative only for a genuinely distinct work-stream. Pairs with cockpit V107.x queue-wall ordering (fresh/live initiatives float to the TOP of the QUEUE wall — was lost when the queue wall replaced the active-roadmap fresh-at-top behaviour). NO Standard/schema bump (uses existing frontmatter + the documented log/ archive convention). 1.24.1 — QX5 execution-registry (operator-directed 2026-06-19): a finished task records what it CHANGED, not just its summary. Runner captures HEAD at turn start (runnerspawn `_turn_start_sha`); on resolution `_persist_task_resolution(start_sha=…)` diffs `start..HEAD` → writes `commit_shas` (the documented v26 frontmatter field) + a "**Ficheros modificados**" markdown list into the `## Resolution` body. NO frontmatter schema change → NO Standard bump (files live in the body, which the cockpit already renders in the archived registry, QX4). Empty when the turn committed nothing (no registry noise); caps 60 files / 25 commits; quiet on any git failure. 1.24.0 — knowledge-tree-unified (operator-directed 2026-06-19): ONE unified knowledge tree. GET /knowledge returns a manifest-driven concept tree — an overlay over context/+docs/+modules/ defined in context/_index.yaml, per-node load=pinned|skeleton|on-demand + spawn_tokens/skeleton_tokens/pinned_tokens budget; GET /knowledge/<id> serves a node's processed body. Feature knowledge.tree.v1 (knowledge_tree/knowledge_node in fsread.py, routes in routes_get.py). Spawn onboarding (_section_project_context) now PREFERS the manifest: injects a KNOWLEDGE MAP (every concept + 1-line desc, ★ for pinned) + the pinned bodies in full, with `GET /knowledge/<id>` fetch ids on on-demand nodes — agents receive the MAP (what exists + where to look), not the whole corpus; legacy per-file serialization stays as fallback when no manifest. Non-destructive: no files moved. 1.23.0 — Standard v26 task resolution record + Queue wall (operator-directed 2026-06-19). TWO halves. (a) RESOLUTION PERSISTENCE: a finished task now durably holds its outcome, not just its spec. On `chat.assistant.final` for ANY conv (runnerloop emit-final path), `_persist_task_resolution` checks the conv's anchored task_id; if that task is `done`, it stamps `completed_at` + `resolved_by` + `resolved_by_conv` on the task .md frontmatter (via _patch_frontmatter) and writes the turn's Output-Contract summary into a `## Resolution` body section (new `_upsert_body_section` in anchorprogress.py — idempotent, preserves the original spec body). statebuild.py now emits these pointers (+ `commit_shas`) in /state.roadmap.tasks so the cockpit paints the per-task "ejecutado · fecha · agente ▸" line + expandable summary that SURVIVES reloads (was session-only before). Quiet on failure — persistence never blocks the final broadcast; only `done` tasks + zero-exit turns record. (b) QUEUE WALL (cockpit): the operator's execution queue is the `next` wall — staging ▶ = POST /initiative/reorder to wall:next (already persists status:next + wall_order), so a CLI agent reading the standard sees the same ordered queue (convention execution-queue-protocol.md). No new daemon endpoint for the queue. 1.22.0 — control-plane source decoupling (operator-directed 2026-06-18). The daemon + cockpit no longer depend on the public marketing website for anything load-bearing — a website cutover (as happened 2026-06-18 when the apex briefly pointed at the SolidStart site) can no longer break daemon self-update or standard refresh. TWO source moves: (a) STANDARD from the API — render.py CANONICAL_PREAMBLE_URL + STANDARD_VERSION_URL now fetch from https://api.meshkore.com/v1/standard/{agent-instructions.md,version} (the always-on Worker serves them as bundled Text/JSON modules); the $schema in /state + the briefing's "canonical schemas" ref point to https://api.meshkore.com/v1/standard.json. (b) DAEMON DISTRIBUTION from the architect subdomain — the auto_update_source default (bootstrap write + the selfupdate/bootupdate/selfupdatesvc/readapi fallbacks) is now https://architect.meshkore.com/reference/cluster/scripts/daemon.py (the cockpit's own Pages deploy hosts the bundle + the loopback TLS bundle at the SAME sub-path, so the TLS-sibling fetch follows). The human-readable standard stays on the public web. Prompt change (schema ref) → golden briefing SHAs regenerated. 1.21.1 — TR1 transient API-error retry shield. claude-code 2.1.145 occasionally fails a long interleaved-thinking + multi-tool turn with `API Error: 400 messages.N.content.M: thinking or redacted_thinking blocks in the latest assistant message cannot be modified` — a CLI bug reconstructing the multi-block assistant message for the tool-loop continuation (the daemon never touches that array; a fresh spawn rebuilds a clean array and the same turn succeeds). Siblings: transient 429/5xx / overloaded / gateway-timeout. These are TRANSPORT failures, not task outcomes — but before this fix the error string got persisted as the turn's chat.assistant.final, POISONING every future briefing via _section_history AND waking the parent architect with a bogus task-failure verdict (field 2026-06-18: master `_onboarding_v1` died exit=1 at content.12, the architect then logged "✗ error — one retry then mark blocked"). ChatRunner._reader_loop now calls `_maybe_retry_transient(result_text)` BEFORE persisting the final: `_is_transient_api_error` matches a conservative allowlist (the thinking-block 400 by signature; 429/5xx/overloaded/gateway/timeout markers; EXCLUDES prompt-too-long + other request-shape 4xx a retry can't fix), and on a confirmed non-zero exit it reaps the child, resets per-turn streaming/anchor/usage state + a fresh stream_id, backs off min(2^n,8)s, and re-spawns the SAME turn (the failed final is never persisted, so _briefing rebuilds clean history). Budget _MAX_TRANSIENT_RETRIES=2 (3 attempts); past that the error surfaces normally. Pure runner-internal change — no wire/API/prompt change, briefing SHAs unchanged. 1.21.0 — roadmap execution: list-scope + archive-confirm. The roadmap-architect SOP now (a) CONFIRMS archival on initiative close — when all tasks are `done` it sets the initiative `status: done`, the daemon's archive-reconcile drops it from the active wall, and the transition block carries an `archived:` line so the operator sees "closed + archived", not merely "done" (blocked tasks → stays active, archived:no); and (b) runs the BOOTSTRAP SCOPE LIST in the operator's given order (no lower-id reordering, no out-of-scope dispatch) — unifying Run All / single-play / future multi-select into one "ordered list" model (a scope of 1 = run it, confirm archive, end-of-pass summary). Prompt-only change to AGENT_PROMPTS["roadmap-architect"]; golden briefing SHAs updated; full suite green. Pairs with cockpit architect-dispatch collapsing ArchitectScope to one ordered-list shape. 1.20.0 — daemon-architecture-v2 COMPLETE (Phases 1-3 + Phase E excellence) + initiative-walls feature. DECOMPOSITION: daemon.py god-file 6017 -> 477 LOC across ~60 single-responsibility modules (mixin pattern; single-file bundle preserved), ZERO behaviour change — golden-master verified at EVERY commit via test_parity (bundle==source) + test_refactor_characterization (briefing SHAs/argv/anchor) + the NEW test_route_coverage endpoint-warranty (51 routes enumerated + live-exercised) + test_frontend_contract (every daemon-client.ts response shape) + a chat-dispatch integration test (fake claude). 207 tests green. PHASE E: daemon/ARCHITECTURE.md LLM navigation map, fsatomic shared atomic-write (DRY across 9 modules), daemon/CHANGELOG.md, mixin-coherence decision. NEW FEATURE (initiative-walls): GET /initiative/walls → {active,next,backlog,archived} ordered by wall_order; POST /initiative/reorder {id,wall,order} writes wall_order frontmatter, maps wall->status (archived=>status:done+archived:true, held by the archived flag so the archive-reconcile can't bounce it), recompacts the wall to 0,1,2,…, broadcasts WS initiative.reordered; /state now emits wall_order; feature flag initiative.walls.v1; back-compat (wall_order optional, missing sorts last by filename). 1.19.0 — daemon-architecture-v2 Phase 1 COMPLETE. Pure refactor, ZERO behaviour change (test_parity + test_refactor_characterization + full suite 118 green at every step). The daemon.py god-file went 6017 -> 4570 LOC (~24%) by extracting cohesive modules, each golden-master-verified: constants.py (DAEMON_VERSION/PORT_RANGE/registry — the dependency-free leaf), http_server.py (PoolHTTPServer + tls/port), cron.py (CronRunner/Scheduler), cluster.py (Cluster + frontmatter + crons validation), bootstrap.py (identity/token/port-pick/registry/migrate), selfupdate.py (VersionWatcher + boot self-update + tls/version helpers), and agent_prompts/ (per-agent-type package, bundler gained subfolder + TYPE_CHECKING-block support). Single-file bundle preserved (bundle.py reads DAEMON_VERSION from constants.py for the early 8KB version marker). Remaining: Phase 2 (the Daemon god-class -> ChatService/CoordinationService/AnchorHandler/QueryService) + Phase 3 (split prompts/routes/runner to <=300). 1.18.0 — daemon-architecture-v2 Phase 1 (modularization, pure refactor, ZERO behaviour change). Extracted from the daemon.py god-file into focused modules, each verified byte-identical via test_parity (bundle == sum of modules) + test_refactor_characterization (briefing SHAs) + full suite 118 green: agent_prompts.py (968 LOC) -> agent_prompts/ package (one fragment per agent type) with bundle.py gaining package-subfolder support + TYPE_CHECKING-block stripping; http_server.py (PoolHTTPServer + tls/port); cron.py (CronRunner/Scheduler + helpers); cluster.py (Cluster + frontmatter + cluster.yaml crons validation). daemon.py 6017 -> ~5270 LOC. Single-file bundle preserved. Remaining (deferred — coupled to DAEMON_VERSION / self-update path): selfupdate.py + bootstrap.py extractions, then Phase 2 (Daemon god-class -> services). 1.17.2 — FIX PoolHTTPServer.server_close crash on partial construction. super().__init__() binds the socket before self._pool is set; a failed bind (port still held by a dying sibling during a restart/self-update re-exec) raised before _pool existed, then cleanup's server_close() did self._pool.shutdown() → AttributeError, MASKING the real bind error and BRICKING the new daemon instead of retrying. Field 2026-06-16: a restart race killed 2 clusters this way. Fix: getattr-guard _pool in server_close. Protects the self-update re-exec path on the whole fleet. 1.17.1 — FIX http-latency metric regressed by keep-alive (py-1.16.2). _http_t0 was stamped in Handler.setup() which under HTTP/1.1 keep-alive runs ONCE PER CONNECTION (one Handler serves many requests), so log_request reported the CONNECTION AGE (e.g. "17838 ms" for an instant OPTIONS on an old kept-alive socket) instead of request latency — misleading the debug/http stream + any latency diagnosis. Fix: stamp _http_t0 per-request in a new handle_one_request override. Cosmetic/observability only — no functional change. 1.17.0 — comms-realtime-sync daemon half (initiative). (D-TURNSNAP-01) ChatSessions.turn_snapshot now reports a conv `current_turn` (live) ONLY when the runner is genuinely still running (`not runner.done.is_set()`) — a finished runner lingers in `_s` until start._wait pops it, and reporting its turn made a reconnecting/refreshing cockpit seed a `streaming:true` bubble that NO future event would clear → the eternal 'Recapping progress…' loader (operator field 2026-06-15: agent had answered but the loader spun until restart). Also added per-conv `_last_final` (set in start._wait when runner.done fires) and surfaced as `last_final_stream_id` in the snapshot so the cockpit can drop any stale live seed whose stream_id ≤ the last final (A-LIVEBUBBLE-01 daemon dependency). (D-UPLOAD-FEEDBACK-01) UploadStore.save_dispatch takes an optional `skipped` out-list (decode_failed / empty / too_large with sizes); chat_dispatch surfaces it as `skipped_uploads` in the 200/202 response so the cockpit can tell the operator an attachment was dropped instead of silently sending text-only. NO wire-breaking change (new optional fields only). Pairs with cockpit V111 (chat rehydration spine + alignment + boot screen). 1.16.2 — HTTP keep-alive (THE root cause of the chronic connection flakiness). The Handler had no `protocol_version`, so it defaulted to HTTP/1.0 = NO keep-alive: the cockpit opened a brand-new TLS connection for EVERY fetch (/state, /chat/conv/<id>/queue per conv, health polls). Each closed into TIME_WAIT; a busy cockpit (ikamiro has 100+ convs) churned hundreds of short-lived TLS connections, the OS ephemeral-port table filled (33k+ TIME_WAIT observed), and NEW connections — including the cockpit's own /state — stalled in SYN_SENT and timed out at the client's 15s cap (blank chats, /state timeouts across all 3 clusters). This is what the 1.15.x backlog/handshake fixes were chasing the symptom of; the disease was per-request connections. Fix: `protocol_version = "HTTP/1.1"` on the Handler (every body response already sends Content-Length; 204/101 are bodyless, so keep-alive is safe) → browser + httpx reuse one connection for many requests, connection count collapses, TIME_WAIT storm gone. Plus `timeout = 30` so a truly-idle kept-alive connection (which blocks a pool worker in handle() waiting for the next request) closes and frees its worker; and max_workers default 64→128 for headroom since kept-alive connections now occupy workers between requests. Verified: tests/test_ws_pool.py extended with a keep-alive reuse assertion. NO wire/API change. 1.16.1 — comms-hardening round 2 (daemon half). (D-STORE-RETENTION-01, finished) TimelineRotator now optionally DELETES archived .gz `delete_days` after rotation, wired from cluster.yaml `storage.retention_days` (absent/0 = keep forever — no surprise history deletion; effective history ≈ age_days + retention_days). New `_delete_old_archives()`. (D-STOREREPORT-01) StorageReport._walk_dir uses os.scandir recursion (DirEntry size, no per-file stat) and CACHE_TTL 5s→30s — a polling cockpit no longer triggers a full multi-thousand-file tree walk every 5s. NO wire/API change. Pairs with cockpit V110 (chat swap-guards, token re-unlock re-verify, OfflinePanel race, clipboard feedback). 1.16.0 — comms-hardening batch (audit 2026-06-15). Daemon-side fixes from the full daemon↔cockpit audit: (D-WS-01) WS read loop moved OFF the bounded request pool onto a dedicated ws-pump thread — a live `/events` socket no longer pins a PoolHTTPServer worker for its whole life (≤64 WS could otherwise starve /state//health//chat of workers). The socket is registered in PoolHTTPServer._ws_hijacked so shutdown_request won't close it when the freed worker returns; the pump owns + closes it. (D-WS-02) Hub.broadcast now snapshots the client set UNDER the lock and SENDS OUTSIDE it (the code previously sent inside _lock despite the docstring, so one stalled client froze every broadcast); WSClient sets SO_SNDTIMEO so a wedged client is dropped within 5s instead of blocking a broadcaster. (D-CHAT-IDX-01) _chat_msg_index memoised on the set of timeline-file (path,mtime,size) — was re-reading + decompressing ALL history on every call incl. per-conv /meta. (D-HTTP-500-01) do_GET/do_POST wrapped in a guard → unexpected handler errors return a 500 JSON instead of dropping the socket with no response (which looked like 'daemon dead'/000 to the cockpit). (D-STORE-RETENTION-01, partial) _conv_meta_load mtime-cached (was re-read+parsed on every getter, 4+×/spawn); the disk-retention/deletion half is deferred (needs a cluster.yaml opt-in policy — won't auto-delete chat history). (D-STORE-ATOMIC-01) ChatQueueManager._write now tmp+fsync+os.replace (atomic), matching the other stores — an interrupted write no longer yields a half-file that _read silently parses to [] (dropping queued turns). (D-FSPOLL-01) _compute_signature uses os.scandir recursion (DirEntry carries stat) instead of rglob+per-file stat → ~halves the 1.5s change-detector's idle syscalls; identical detection. (D-TEST-ISO-01) MESHKORE_PORTS_FILE env overrides the sticky port-registry path so the test suite stops polluting the operator's real ~/.meshkore/ports.json. NO wire/API change; pairs with cockpit V109 (boot-gate escape + WS same-port reconnect + error surfacing). 1.15.2 — defer TLS handshake off the accept loop. The daemon wrapped the LISTENING socket with ctx.wrap_socket(server_side=True) at its default do_handshake_on_connect=True, so the TLS handshake of every accepted connection ran INSIDE accept() — i.e. in the single serve_forever accept thread. A slow or half-open client (browsers open speculative/pre-connect sockets; the cockpit opens many to whichever project is actively polled, e.g. an offline one on its 2s /health watch) blocked that accept loop mid-handshake, so the kernel refused every other pending connection → intermittent ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED (HTTP 000), worst on the most-polled cluster (field 2026-06-15: ikamiro ~40% /health failures while idle, cavioca/meshkore near-0). The py-1.15.1 backlog bump (5→128) reduced burst refusals but couldn't fix this because the bottleneck was the accept thread itself, not the queue depth. Fix: wrap the listener with do_handshake_on_connect=False (accept() now returns an un-handshaked SSLSocket immediately) and complete the handshake in PoolHTTPServer.process_request_thread — i.e. on a pool worker (bounded 10s handshake timeout). A slow handshake now ties up one of max_workers threads instead of the sole accept loop. NO API/wire change. Completes the connection-reliability fix begun in 1.15.1. 1.15.1 — listen-backlog fix (HTTP connection-refusal under cockpit boot burst). PoolHTTPServer(ThreadingHTTPServer) inherited socketserver's default request_queue_size=5, so the socket listen() backlog was 5. A cockpit boot fires a burst of ~30 concurrent connections (GET /state + GET /chat/snapshot + a GET per initiative body + the /events WS upgrade); with a backlog of 5 the kernel REFUSED the excess → intermittent ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED (HTTP 000) that stranded the cockpit mid-hydration (BootingPanel stuck on "Snapshot del roadmap"/"Historial de conversaciones" forever) and is the same effect behind the test_pool_bounds_concurrent_requests 18/50 result. The class docstring's claim that excess requests "queue at the OS-accept layer (much higher than any sane workload)" was simply wrong — the accept backlog was the tiny default. Fix: `request_queue_size = 128` on PoolHTTPServer (socketserver passes it to socket.listen()). 128 absorbs any realistic single-cockpit burst. NO API/wire change. Pairs with cockpit V108 (switchProject re-entrancy guard + bounded fetch timeout) which removes the front-end's infinite switch loop and infinite-hang on a stalled fetch. 1.15.0 — STABLE per-cluster ports (anti-drift, initiative `daemon-port-stability`). ROOT CAUSE of the cockpit "doing weird things" with 3 projects on one box: `_pick_port` honoured a requested port then SILENTLY drifted to the first free port in 5570–5589 on any collision — so when several daemons (re)booted near-simultaneously they scrambled onto each other's ports (field 2026-06-14: ikamiro req 5573→bound 5571, meshkore req 5572→bound 5573, cavioca req 5570→bound 5572), and nobody pinned a stable port, so the cockpit's localStorage rail kept dialing the OLD port (ikamiro→5570, dead) and `switchToPort`-thrashed across the range. Fix: a machine-global sticky registry `~/.meshkore/ports.json` (cluster_id→port) is now the source of truth. `_pick_port(paths, cluster_id, cli_override, yaml_port)` resolves: (1) explicit `--port` wins + rewrites the sticky entry; (2) the cluster's sticky registry assignment; (3) a fresh seed from cluster.yaml `architect.port` / last `.runtime/port` / lowest-free, then claimed + persisted. The chosen port is then VALIDATED with an anti-steal guard: if busy and `/health` shows a DIFFERENT live cluster_id, we refuse to steal — reassign to a fresh free port and persist; if held by our OWN cluster_id (stale/dying instance or a self-update re-exec) we keep it and let the bind path reclaim. `_claim` re-reads+merges the registry so a sibling registering in the race window isn't clobbered, and `_lowest_free` skips ports reserved by other clusters AND live-checks `_port_free`, so even a simultaneous-boot race converges to distinct ports. New helpers `_last_runtime_port` / `_registry_read` / `_registry_write` / `_probe_cluster_id`; new consts `_PORT_REGISTRY_DIR`/`_PORT_REGISTRY_FILE`. Self-update re-exec is unaffected (it passes explicit `--port` = current port → step 1 returns it immediately, MESHKORE_REEXEC_WAIT_PORT bind-wait still reclaims the socket). NO wire/API change; cockpit needs no change — stable ports stop the thrash and its existing scan-by-cluster_id reconciles the stale localStorage entry on next probe. 1.14.11 — queue-flush user event (QF2) + anchor slug normalization (AS1). (QF2) The disk-queue flush path (`_maybe_flush_chat_queue`) called `_spawn_chat_turn` WITHOUT first persisting a `chat.user` timeline event — unlike `chat_dispatch` — so a flushed queued message was missing from the chat wall AND vanished from history on reload (only the agent's triggered response showed, orphaned). Extracted `_persist_user_event(conv, text, author, attachments)` as the single source for 'operator message enters the conversation'; `chat_dispatch` and the flush path now both call it. `_append_timeline` stamps ts → the user bubble sorts chronologically before the assistant final. Frontend unchanged (it already ingests `chat.user`; `queue.item.sent` drops the strip entry). Operator field report 2026-06-14 (IKA/circle: A113's deploy reply showed with no preceding user bubble). (AS1) Anchor `{"i":...}` resolution now normalizes identity-safe before validating — `strip().lstrip("#").lower()` — so the common slip of pasting the `#`-display id (`#I32` → `I32-...`) as a slug is recovered instead of hard-rejected with "invalid initiative slug". Same for `new_t.initiative`. The display-id PREFIX (`I32-`) is NOT stripped (would risk anchoring to the wrong initiative); that's handled prompt-side: prompts.py now states `i` is the lowercase file-stem slug, never the `#`-display id, with a ✗/✓ example. Anchor rejection remains harmless to chat history/log (text always persists). NO wire/API change. 1.14.10 — FIX anchor marker bracket fragility (LAL). The anchor wire protocol's canonical marker uses the mathematical white square brackets ⟦ ⟧ (U+27E6/U+27E7), but LLMs do NOT reliably emit rare Unicode glyphs — they routinely normalise them to ASCII `[anchor]` / `[[anchor]]` (or CJK 【anchor】). When that happened the strict `⟦anchor⟧`-only regex in ChatRunner matched NOTHING, so the marker was (a) never parsed → `_handle_anchor` never ran → no initiative/task creation, no conv_meta initiative_id/task_id persist, no `conv.anchor_*` WS event → the cockpit roadmap never lit the live spinner on the initiative/task being worked, AND (b) never stripped → the raw `[anchor] {...}` line leaked into the chat bubble (the very internal protocol data the operator said must stay hidden). Both symptoms, ONE root cause. Fix: ChatRunner `_ANCHOR_RE` / `_ANCHOR_PROGRESS_RE` now accept any common bracket rendering (⟦ 〚 【 [[ [ … ⟧ 〛 】 ]] ]) via shared `_ANCHOR_OPEN`/`_ANCHOR_CLOSE` classes; the `_strip_anchor_progress` + `_strip_all_anchor_markers` fast-path guards switched from `"⟦anchor…" in text` to bracket-agnostic substring checks. Briefing still teaches the canonical ⟦ ⟧ (prompts.py unchanged) — parser is liberal in what it accepts (Postel). The `-progress` variant can't be mis-eaten by the plain `anchor` regex because the close-bracket must follow `anchor` immediately (a `-` blocks it). Operator field report 2026-06-13 (ikamiro: `[anchor]` visible in chat + roadmap spinner never lit despite a valid anchor decision). NO wire/API change. ALSO 1.14.10 — FIX silent auto-update breakage since the DM3 modularization. VersionWatcher._fetch_remote_version HTTP Range-fetches only the FIRST 8 KB (`_FETCH_BYTES`) of the published bundle and parses `^DAEMON_VERSION`; but bundle.py inlines daemon.py LAST, so the canonical DAEMON_VERSION assignment sits ~334 KB deep — past the 8 KB window — so the fetch returned None and NO cluster auto-updated (published stuck at py-1.14.4 since 1.14.4/1.14.5's modularize-2/3, field-confirmed 2026-06-13). Fix is in bundle.py: it now echoes an EARLY `DAEMON_VERSION = "<ver>"` marker into the bundle header (right after `from __future__`), so the version-watcher's 8 KB fetch finds it. Heals detection for every already-deployed watcher (they read the first 8 KB of the new published file). The canonical assignment + changelog is still inlined from daemon.py below; Python reassigns the identical value (no behaviour change). 1.14.9 — FIX recurring ChatSessions._lock deadlock. ChatSessions._wait (the per-runner completion thread) invoked the on_idle / on_chain callbacks WHILE holding self._lock. Both re-enter ChatSessions (on_idle -> Daemon._maybe_flush_chat_queue -> has()/start(); on_chain -> _spawn_chat_turn -> start()) and broadcast via the Hub — self._lock is a plain non-reentrant threading.Lock, so the _wait thread self-deadlocked, kept the lock forever, and every list_active()/has()/reap_dead() (i.e. /chat/snapshot) hung. This is the intermittent ikamiro hang (cockpit stuck on "Historial de conversaciones"; agent rail flooded with stale localStorage convMeta because the snapshot never hydrated to prune/filter). py-1.14.6 made it FAR more frequent: the has()-guard it added at the top of _maybe_flush_chat_queue re-locks on EVERY turn-completion, not just when a disk queue item exists. Fix: capture idle/chain decision under the lock, then call the callbacks AFTER releasing it (slot already popped/cleared, so the re-entrant has()/start() see clean state; the 1.14.6 idempotency guard absorbs the dispatch race). No wire/API change. 1.14.8 — standard-version drift detection (detect + surface only). AgentInstructionsRenderer.check_standard_drift() fetches meshkore.com/standard/version on the VersionWatcher tick, compares to the cluster's pinned `.meshkore/STANDARD_VERSION`, and on the transition into drift logs + broadcasts a `standard.drift` {local, latest} WS event. `/health.standard` = {version, latest, drift} so the cockpit can render a "Standard vN available — review CHANGELOG / dispatch catch-up" banner (mirrors the daemon-outdated flow). Deliberately does NOT bump STANDARD_VERSION and does NOT apply the structural CHANGELOG catch-up (folder/schema migrations) — that stays LLM/operator work per Standard §11; a daemon rewriting the layout unattended is how clusters break. The §17 preamble/per-CLI instructions are ALREADY kept fresh unconditionally by refresh_from_remote() (py-1.14.7) regardless of the version number, so instructions never go stale even while a structural catch-up is pending. Feature flag `standard.drift.v1`. 1.14.7 — §17 agent-instructions render loop (ADI-01). New module render.py / AgentInstructionsRenderer (Paths+Hub, zero daemon coupling, same shape as the registries). Closes the long-standing gap where §17 mandated the daemon keep the per-CLI instruction files in sync but NO code did it — CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md/GEMINI.md drifted behind the canonical preamble (the snapshots item §20 never reached them; field-confirmed 2026-06-13). Two idempotent jobs: (a) render_targets() mirrors `.meshkore/public/AGENT_INSTRUCTIONS.md` into the root per-CLI files each CLI auto-loads — boot-synced once (heals older-daemon drift) + driven by a 3 s mtime watch on the source so an operator edit fans out within seconds; the two v19+ targets (`.cursor/rules/meshkore.mdc`, `.clinerules`) are written only when the cluster STANDARD_VERSION ≥ 19. (b) refresh_from_remote() fetches the canonical preamble at meshkore.com/standard/agent-instructions.md and overwrites the MESHKORE_PREAMBLE block of AGENT_INSTRUCTIONS.md IN PLACE (OPERATOR_CONTENT preserved byte-for-byte), driven on the existing VersionWatcher 30-min tick INDEPENDENT of the auto_update opt-out (a doc refresh is not a code upgrade). Idempotent throughout (skips unchanged files → no disk churn / no WS spam). New WS events `agent_instructions.rendered` {files} + `agent_instructions.preamble_refreshed`. Feature flag `agent_instructions.render.v1`. bundle.py MODULES gains render.py (after registries.py). Reopens/closes ADI-01 which was marked done at the 2026-06-09 bootstrap but never shipped the maintenance loop. 1.14.6 — idle chat-queue flush (QF1). The disk chat-queue (ChatQueueManager, `.meshkore/queues/<conv>.json`) was drained ONLY by the on_idle hook that fires on turn-COMPLETION. So a conv that went idle with items still queued — after a daemon restart / py-1.14.3 self-update re-exec (in-memory ChatSessions + its _wait thread are gone), a session reaped abnormally (reap_dead pops the slot without firing on_idle), or an enqueue into an already-idle conv — left the queue stranded forever ("N WAITING · runs after the current turn" with no current turn to finish). New `Daemon._flush_idle_chat_queues()` sweeps every disk queue and flushes the head of any conv with NO turn in flight; flushing re-registers on_idle via `_spawn_chat_turn` (agent_type/id/model resolved from the persisted conv sidecar), so the rest drains turn-by-turn. Wired into `ChatSessionReaper._sweep` Phase 3 (boot sweep resumes update-stranded queues; 30s tick is the safety net). `_maybe_flush_chat_queue` gained an in-flight idempotency guard + bool return so the on_idle and reaper triggers can't double-spawn. New `ChatQueueManager.conv_ids()`. Operator field report 2026-06-13: IKA cluster queue stuck at 2 WAITING after a mid-session daemon update. NO wire/API change — cockpit unaffected. 1.14.5 — daemon-modularize-3. More pure code-movement, continuing the split toward small files. Three new modules: agent_prompts.py (the ~940-line AGENT_PROMPTS data dict, out of prompts.py so the briefing LOGIC stays small), registries.py (LinksRegistry + ProtocolsRegistry + their YAML/frontmatter helpers — zero daemon coupling), runs.py (RunStore + TimelineRotator — zero daemon coupling). daemon.py drops ~6280 → ~5600 LOC (and ~9360 → ~5600 across modularize-2+3). Bundle MODULES order now paths→utils→hub→registries→runs→storage→chat→agent_prompts→prompts→runner→quota→routes. quota.py/daemon.py keep importing AGENT_PROMPTS from prompts (prompts re-exports it). STOPPED before extracting cron + version-watcher/self-update: cron is interleaved across 3 regions with the credentials validator, and the self-update path (py-1.14.3 same-port re-exec) has near-zero test coverage — extracting either risks the no-behaviour-change guarantee on under-tested code. The `Daemon` god-class (~3400 LOC) is the remaining lever and needs a redesign (shared self-state), not a move. NO behaviour change — 97/97 tests green incl. bundle parity + golden-master characterization. 1.14.4 — daemon-modularize-2. Pure code-movement refactor extracting the two pieces the first modularize pass (py-1.13.x) deferred: ChatRunner (~760 LOC, the claude-code subprocess driver) → runner.py, and the prompt machinery (AGENT_PROMPTS registry + _agent_manifest + _agent_type_* + ProjectState + StateIntegrityChecker + _conversation_history + BriefingPipeline) → prompts.py. daemon.py drops 9359 → ~6280 LOC. Shared pure helpers also relocated to utils.py (parse_simple_yaml/parse_frontmatter family, _append_timeline, _find_tls_bundle, _daemon_base_url) so the extracted modules import top-down (utils → prompts → runner) with no `from daemon import` at module scope. quota.py's _agent_manifest/AGENT_PROMPTS shadow-stubs replaced by a real `from prompts import`. The architect SOP's `MeshKore: <ver>` trailer is now substituted at BriefingPipeline.build() (placeholder __MESHKORE_VERSION__) instead of f-string-interpolated at dict-load, because the prompts section loads before DAEMON_VERSION is defined in the bundle. bundle.py MODULES gains prompts.py + runner.py (order: …chat → prompts → runner → quota → routes) and now strips `from daemon import` lines (the build() version import resolves via the flat namespace). NO behaviour change — 97/97 tests green incl. bundle parity + a new golden-master characterization suite (briefing SHA per agent type, manifest snapshot, anchor-strip, --model/--effort argv). 1.14.3 — same-port self-update re-exec. self_update() previously spawned the replacement on a NEW free port and let the cockpit re-discover it (fragile: port hunting, WS-fatal, operator-visible "taking longer than usual"). Now the new process re-execs on the SAME port: the old daemon spawns the child with MESHKORE_REEXEC_WAIT_PORT=1, explicitly server_close()s its listen socket, and os._exit(0)s after a 0.6s flush delay; the child's serve_forever retries the bind for ~12s (250ms cadence) until the port frees, then comes up on the identical port. The cockpit's WS simply reconnects to the same URL — no port change, no port-recovery scan, no front-end reload. Falls back to SystemExit if the port never frees in 12s (old daemon stuck). 1.14.2 — MP3 effort pass-through + full model ids. `/chat/dispatch` now accepts `effort` (low/medium/high/xhigh/max), persisted in conv_meta, resolved by `_conv_meta_get_effort`, and injected as `claude-code --effort <level>` by ChatRunner.spawn (skipped on the 'default' sentinel). This is claude-code's reasoning-depth dial — the cockpit's "thinking" control. `_conv_meta_set` no longer lowercases the model so pinned ids (claude-opus-4-8) survive verbatim alongside the opus/sonnet/haiku aliases. conv.created/meta_updated broadcasts + /chat/snapshot.convs[] now carry both `model` and `effort`. Pairs with cockpit NewAgentWizard which exposes a versioned model catalog (aliases + pinned 4.x) + an effort picker. 1.14.1 — context tree endpoint (Standard v14 §3.5). New `context_tree()` method walks `.meshkore/context/` and `GET /context` serves the folder/file tree (per-file title/updated/status from frontmatter + word count + §3.5 over_cap flag) with tree-level total_words/token_estimate/budget_tokens/over_budget/warnings; `GET /context/<path>` serves a single file body (reuses `_serve_meshkore_file` rooted at context_dir, same path-traversal defence). Fixes the cockpit's Context tab which logged `GET /context 404` on every open (ContextPanel.tsx → daemon-client.contextTree, shipped V107.34 against a daemon endpoint that never existed). Feature flag `context.tree.v1`. New `paths.context_dir`. 1.14.0 — universal Output Contract (OC1). The single weak "Reply concisely" line in `_section_core_rules` is replaced by a prominent `## Output contract` section that EVERY agent type inherits every turn (previously only the architect had a LENGTH BUDGETS table; custom/audit/deploy/db/docs had no length guidance, so an audit-style turn dumped ~50 lines). The contract mandates: lead with a ≤8-line summary (problem + files touched + N-step plan), put ALL detail inside native HTML `<details>` blocks (one per file/topic, blank line after `</summary>` so inner markdown renders), no detail-prose at the top level, no process narration. Pairs with cockpit V107.36 which renders `<details>` natively + stops auto-expanding fresh finals (the auto-expand was un-clamping the very 50-line walls the operator complained about). Operator field report 2026-06-12: agent A108 audit reply was unreadable. Convention: `.meshkore/docs/conventions/output-contract.md`. 1.13.3 — model pass-through (MP1) + chat usage broadcast (CU1). Two initiatives shipped together. (a) The cockpit's NewAgentWizard model picker (auto/opus/sonnet/haiku) now wires end-to-end: `/chat/dispatch` accepts `model`, stored in conv_meta, ChatRunner.spawn injects `--model <id>` into claude-code argv (skipped when `auto`/None — lets the CLI use its default). Chained turns inherit. (b) ChatRunner captures `usage` + `total_cost_usd` from the SDK's terminal `result` event, ChatSessions accumulates cumulative-per-conv totals (input/output/cache_read/cache_creation/cost_usd/turns), `chat.usage` WS event fires after each turn final, and `/chat/snapshot.convs[].usage` exposes the cumulative dict on every snapshot. Cockpit can render `12.3k in · 4.5k out · $0.15` per agent. 1.13.2 — anchor-strip-final fix. The Claude SDK `result` event was bypassing the per-delta anchor stripper (which only runs on `_cumulative_text`). When the SDK emitted a final `result` block, daemon preferred that text and the leading `⟦anchor⟧ {...}` line + any `⟦anchor-progress⟧ {...}` lines leaked into the persisted timeline + the broadcast `chat.assistant.final`. New `_strip_all_anchor_markers` sweep applied to `final_text` before persisting. Pure scrubbing — the side-effects already ran during streaming. Operator field report 2026-06-12: agent A108 anchor marker visible in chat bubble. 1.13.1 — SRL2 state-recovery-loop snapshot expansion. `/chat/snapshot` (and `/chat/convs`) now carry, for each live conv, a `current_turn` dict (started_at + stream_id + partial_text up to 16 KB + tool_calls_count + deltas_seen) and a `queue` list (the in-memory ChatSessions.pending). Lets a cockpit that just connected mid-turn rehydrate the assistant bubble exactly where it was — restores "Reviewing the roadmap…" output + QUEUED user bubbles + the "preparing" indicator after a browser refresh. Both fields are OPTIONAL on the wire — older cockpits ignore them. New feature: daemon.snapshot.turn_state.v1. SRL1 (e647746) added ChatRunner.started_at / deltas_seen / tool_calls_count attrs that SRL2 reads via getattr. 1.13.0 — LAL3 live-anchor-loop side-effects. The single weak "Reply concisely" line in `_section_core_rules` is replaced by a prominent `## Output contract` section that EVERY agent type inherits every turn (previously only the architect had a LENGTH BUDGETS table; custom/audit/deploy/db/docs had no length guidance, so an audit-style turn dumped ~50 lines). The contract mandates: lead with a ≤8-line summary (problem + files touched + N-step plan), put ALL detail inside native HTML `<details>` blocks (one per file/topic, blank line after `</summary>` so inner markdown renders), no detail-prose at the top level, no process narration. Pairs with cockpit V107.36 which renders `<details>` natively + stops auto-expanding fresh finals (the auto-expand was un-clamping the very 50-line walls the operator complained about). Operator field report 2026-06-12: agent A108 audit reply was unreadable. Convention: `.meshkore/docs/conventions/output-contract.md`. 1.13.3 — model pass-through (MP1) + chat usage broadcast (CU1). Two initiatives shipped together. (a) The cockpit's NewAgentWizard model picker (auto/opus/sonnet/haiku) now wires end-to-end: `/chat/dispatch` accepts `model`, stored in conv_meta, ChatRunner.spawn injects `--model <id>` into claude-code argv (skipped when `auto`/None — lets the CLI use its default). Chained turns inherit. (b) ChatRunner captures `usage` + `total_cost_usd` from the SDK's terminal `result` event, ChatSessions accumulates cumulative-per-conv totals (input/output/cache_read/cache_creation/cost_usd/turns), `chat.usage` WS event fires after each turn final, and `/chat/snapshot.convs[].usage` exposes the cumulative dict on every snapshot. Cockpit can render `12.3k in · 4.5k out · $0.15` per agent. 1.13.2 — anchor-strip-final fix. The Claude SDK `result` event was bypassing the per-delta anchor stripper (which only runs on `_cumulative_text`). When the SDK emitted a final `result` block, daemon preferred that text and the leading `⟦anchor⟧ {...}` line + any `⟦anchor-progress⟧ {...}` lines leaked into the persisted timeline + the broadcast `chat.assistant.final`. New `_strip_all_anchor_markers` sweep applied to `final_text` before persisting. Pure scrubbing — the side-effects already ran during streaming. Operator field report 2026-06-12: agent A108 anchor marker visible in chat bubble. 1.13.1 — SRL2 state-recovery-loop snapshot expansion. `/chat/snapshot` (and `/chat/convs`) now carry, for each live conv, a `current_turn` dict (started_at + stream_id + partial_text up to 16 KB + tool_calls_count + deltas_seen) and a `queue` list (the in-memory ChatSessions.pending). Lets a cockpit that just connected mid-turn rehydrate the assistant bubble exactly where it was — restores "Reviewing the roadmap…" output + QUEUED user bubbles + the "preparing" indicator after a browser refresh. Both fields are OPTIONAL on the wire — older cockpits ignore them. New feature: daemon.snapshot.turn_state.v1. SRL1 (e647746) added ChatRunner.started_at / deltas_seen / tool_calls_count attrs that SRL2 reads via getattr. 1.13.0 — LAL3 live-anchor-loop side-effects.
